==English==

{{wikipedia|Knitting}}

===Etymology===
Akin to Old Norse {{term|knýta}} (Danish {{term|knytte}}) and Northern German {{term|knütten}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/'nɪt/}}
* {{audio|en-uk-knit.ogg|Audio (UK)}}
*: {{rhymes|ɪt}}

====Homophones====
* [[nit]]

===Verb===
{{en-verb|knit|t|ed}}

# To turn [[thread]] or [[yarn]] into a piece of fabric by forming loops that are pulled through each other. This can be done by hand with [[needle]]s or by machine.
# {{figurative}} To join closely and firmly together.
#: ''The joint fight for survival '''knitted''' the men closely together.''
# {{intransitive}} To become closely and firmly joined.
# To combine from various elements.
#: ''The witness '''knitted''' his testimony from contradictory pieces of hearsay.''

